`git_status` module reports branch to be `up_to_date` when untracked


#### Expected Behavior

None of `up_to_date`, `ahead`, `diverged` and `behind` should be displayed if the current branch is untracked.
This is a regression, introduced by the switch to gitoxide. Setting use_git_executable = true reverts back to the previous correct behavior.

Bonus points: consider adding an `untracked` configuration option

issue.body:
Subsquare does not seem to automatically detect or attempt to sign with ones existing governance proxy relationship.  It does appear Subsquare has a field to indicate one's desired proxy account.
https://polkadot.subsquare.io/settings/proxy

When this field is populated with the polkadot address of the proxy account, the following error occurs:

I've verified the proxy relationship in polkadot.js.org, and have used the indicated governance proxy to sign transactions for many years.

comment.body: > Additionally, a minor detail but I feel like the way subsquare describes proxying is 'reversed'. Proxy addresses sign transactions on behalf of the proxied address. > > > It seems like this should read _"All your transactions will be submitted on behalf of your address by this proxy address:"_ > > Also the way you phrased it _"You don't have to set a proxy on the settings page if you want to sign a transaction for a proxy address"_ I would say that this way _"You don't have to set a proxy on the settings page if you want your proxy address to sign a transaction for your account address"_ > > I hope this feedback is helpful Sorry, our copywriting have some misleadings. The input address should be the proxied address. For a proxy relationship, with `A-> B`, then A is the proxied account, B is the proxy account. Then we should login with B and set A as the proxied account. After settings, B will be able to sign transactions on behalf of A. I hope this description can make things clear and we will correct the copywriting.

comment.body:
I would prefer `Ascon_p` just be initialized at construction with the number of rounds to use for init + processing plus the byte rate and the entire (prehashed) 5 word initial state. Then `absorb`, `squeeze`, and `finish` can all be defined in a cpp file instead of being inlined, and `permute` is no longer parameterized at compile time.

Unless the compiler is *very* smart, I'm pretty sure what would happen with this is that as various Ascon types (AEAD, XOF, ...) are added, we'll end up shipping 2*N different implementations of the Ascon permutation logic, since each depends on a `Params` which is going to be unique for that usage, and then for each type we get two  `permute` that different on both `Params` and the round count.

comment.body:
So while being able to precompute the initial state is a nice trick I really don't like how the definition of the permutation leaks out into all callers of the Ascon types. Which at least since it's no longer a public type is still constrainted to internal, but why should `hash.cpp` or `aead.cpp` care about the permutation?

It just seems a lot more straightforward to copy the constants in Table 12.

An analogy I would make is that SHA-256's round constants are the cube roots of primes, and we *could* constexpr compute these - but would doing so make the code easier or harder to understand?

pull_request.title: NIST SP.800-232: Ascon-Hash256
pull_request.body:
As requested in https://github.com/randombit/botan/issues/4943

This adds a stand-alone implementation of the Ascon permutation that should be reusable for the XOFs and the AEAD (potentially requiring some extension, though). The permutation is templated for the number of rounds, because this differs depending on the use case.

Note that this is not really optimized yet. For instance, the code in `absorb` and `squeeze` is essentially copied from the Keccak permutation and could be either shared by both, or optimized for Ascon (where the hash block size is always a single 64-bit word).

pull_request.body:
As requested in https://github.com/randombit/botan/issues/4943

This adds a stand-alone implementation of the Ascon permutation that should be reusable for the XOFs and the AEAD (potentially requiring some extension, though). The permutation is templated for the number of rounds, because this differs depending on the use case.

Note that this is not really optimized yet. For instance, the code in `absorb` and `squeeze` is essentially copied from the Keccak permutation and could be either shared by both, or optimized for Ascon (where the hash block size is always a single 64-bit word).
